04677nam a22005535i 9780822387121DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223871217 a10.1515/97808223871212doi  a(DE-B1597)554427  a(OCoLC)1226680269  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aEdwards, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMorocco Bound :bDisorienting America’s Maghreb, from Casablanca to the Marrakech Express /cBrian Edwards; ed. by Donald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (383 p.) :b27 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists : 1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Morocco Bound, 1942–1973 -- tI. Taking Casablanca -- t1. American Orientalism: Taking Casablanca -- t2. Sheltering Screens: Paul Bowles and Foreign Relations -- tII. Queer Tangier -- t3. Tangier(s): The Multiple Cold War Contexts of the International Zone -- t4. Disorienting the National Subject: Burroughs’s Tangier, Hitchcock’s Marrakech -- t5. Two Serious Authors: Jane Bowles, Mohammed Mrabet, and the Politics of Translation -- tIII. Marrakech Express -- t6. Hippie Orientalism: The Interpretation of Countercultures -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil attention shifted to the Middle East in the early 1970s, Americans turned most often toward the Maghreb—Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, and the Sahara—for their understanding of “the Arab.” In Morocco Bound, Brian T. Edwards examines American representations of the Maghreb during three pivotal decades—from 1942, when the United States entered the North African campaign of World War II, through 1973. He reveals how American film and literary, historical, journalistic, and anthropological accounts of the region imagined the role of the United States in a world it seemed to dominate at the same time that they displaced domestic social concerns—particularly about race relations—onto an “exotic” North Africa.Edwards reads a broad range of texts to recuperate the disorienting possibilities for rethinking American empire. Examining work by William Burroughs, Jane Bowles, Ernie Pyle, A. J. Liebling, Jane Kramer, Alfred Hitchcock, Clifford Geertz, James Michener, Ornette Coleman, General George S. Patton, and others, he puts American texts in conversation with an archive of Maghrebi responses. Whether considering Warner Brothers’ marketing of the movie Casablanca in 1942, journalistic representations of Tangier as a city of excess and queerness, Paul Bowles’s collaboration with the Moroccan artist Mohammed Mrabet, the hippie communities in and around Marrakech in the 1960s and early 1970s, or the writings of young American anthropologists working nearby at the same time, Edwards illuminates the circulation of American texts, their relationship to Maghrebi history, and the ways they might be read so as to reimagine the role of American culture in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAsianistszUnited States. 0aHistoriographyzMorocco. 0aOrientalismzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aPease, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387121zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387121423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822387121/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist